===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|阜|昜|ls=psc|c1=s|c2=p|t1=hill|t2=sunshine}}. {{och-l|*昜}} is the original character for this word, {{och-l|*阜}} was added later.

===Etymology===
Either {{der|zh|sit}} or a {{w|Mainland Southeast Asia linguistic area|Mainland Southeast Asian (MSEA)}} Wanderwort; compare {{cog|my|လင်း||bright}}, {{cog|lep|ᰣᰦᰜᰩᰵ|tr=a-lóṅ|t=reflective light}}, {{cog|th|ปลั่ง||bright; shiny}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

STEDT provisionally sets up {{cog|tbq-kuk-pro|*klaaŋ-I, klaan-II||shine; light; bright}} and compares it to the following:
* {{och-l|陽|sunshine}}
* {{och-l|景|bright; scenery}}
* {{och-l|鏡|mirror}}
* {{och-l|亮|bright}}
* {{och-l|章|brilliant, splendid; rule; emblem; display (v.)}}

Taken together, the Chinese, Lepcha, Kuki-Chin, and Burmese cognates imply a {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*laŋ|t=to be bright}}.

